    "description": "On July 17, 1981, a tea dance filled the Kansas City Hyatt Regency atrium while suspended walkways crossed overhead. This video follows the drawing change that doubled the load at a critical hanger-rod connection and shows how an orderly approval process accepted the wrong load path.\n\nThe story is not just that a connection failed. It is how a structural change moved through drawings, assumptions, reviews, and warnings until the system treated a changed load path like paperwork.\n\nChapters:\n00:00 The Tea Dance\n01:32 The Original Load Path\n03:11 The Revision\n05:08 The Category Error\n08:05 The Warning Signs\n12:43 Everything Was In Order\n\nSources and references:\nNIST/NBS Building Science Series 143: Investigation of the Kansas City Hyatt Regency Walkways Collapse\nhttps://doi.org/10.6028/NBS.BSS.143\n\nNIST: Walkway Collapse, Kansas City, Missouri, 1981\nhttps://www.nist.gov/el/walkway-collapse-kansas-city-missouri-1981\n\nASCE Civil Engineering Source: The Hyatt Regency Walkway Collapse\nhttps://www.asce.org/publications-and-news/civil-engineering-source/civil-engineering-magazine/article/2007/01/the-hyatt-regency-walkway-collapse/\n",
